Replaced ``assert`` statements used for runtime validation in :class:`~icalendar.parser.content_line.Contentline` and in the internal ``_escape_char``, ``_unescape_char``, and ``_foldline`` helpers of :mod:`icalendar.parser.string` with explicit ``raise`` statements. ``assert`` is removed by Python's ``-O`` optimization flag, so these guards were previously silently skipped under ``-O``, allowing an unescaped newline to reach :meth:`~icalendar.parser.content_line.Contentline.to_ical` and produce output that violates :rfc:`5545#section-3.1`'s content line structure. The guards now raise :exc:`ValueError` for invalid newline content and :exc:`TypeError` for invalid argument types, regardless of the interpreter's optimization level. AI disclosure: I used Claude (Anthropic, Sonnet 5, via Claude Code) to research the issue, draft this change, and write its tests; I reviewed and validated the output locally, including manual verification under ``python -O``. @gagana2023
